To end this section, we demonstrate the closure of the supersymmetry
algebra on the tensors. This is more complicated, since the commutator
only closes modulo gauge transformations and equations of motion. The
latter property is rather unusual: Recall that a supersymmetry
commutator is at most linear in derivatives, whereas bosonic equations
of motion are second-order differential equations. This is why usually
one only finds fermionic field equations, in the commutators evaluated
on the fermions. For tensors, a second derivative can be produced by
introducing an explicit spacetime coordinate dependence according to the
identity (which is valid for any vector, not just for the dual field
strength of some tensor)
 * 
as was first noticed in (see also for a deeper
explanation of the explicit coordinate dependence). The first term on
the right-hand side is proportional to the (linearized) field equation
of a tensor, while the second term has the form of a gauge
transformation.

